{
  "The coefficient of variation (CV) is calculated as:": "",
  "(Standard deviation / Mean) × 100%": "",
  "(Variance / Mean) × 100%": "",
  "(Range / Mean) × 100%": "",
  "(Mean / Standard deviation) × 100%": "",
  "CV = (SD / Mean) × 100%, expressing the standard deviation as a percentage of the mean.": "",
  "The main advantage of the CV over the standard deviation is that the CV:": "",
  "Ignores the mean entirely and calculates variability without any reference to center": "",
  "Only works with normally distributed data and cannot be applied to skewed data sets": "",
  "Is unit-free, allowing comparison of variability between data sets with different units or scales": "",
  "Is always smaller than the standard deviation regardless of the units or scale used": "",
  "Because the CV is a ratio of SD to mean, the units cancel, making it ideal for comparing variability across different measurement scales.": "",
  "Data set A has mean = 50 and SD = 10. Data set B has mean = 200 and SD = 30. Which has greater relative variability?": "",
  "Cannot be compared": "",
  "Set A, because CV = 20% > 15%": "",
  "Set B, because SD = 30 > 10": "",
  "They have equal relative variability": "",
  "CV_A = (10/50)×100% = 20%. CV_B = (30/200)×100% = 15%. Set A has greater relative variability despite having a smaller SD.": "",
